ht/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis study provides a radical reassessment of the English Reformation. No one in eighteenth-century England thought that they were living during ‘the Enlightenment’; instead, they saw themselves as facing the religious, intellectual and political problems unleashed by the Reformation, which began in the sixteenth century. Moreover, they faced those problems in the aftermath of two bloody seventeenth-century political and religious revolutions. This book examines how the eighteenth-century English debated the causes and consequences of those revolutions and the thing they thought had caused them, the Reformation. It draws on a wide array of manuscript sources to show how authors crafted and pitched their works.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aReformationzGreat Britain. 0aReligion and politicszEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aChristology.  aChurch and state.  aDeism.  aEnlightenment.  aHistorical scholarship.  aMethodism.  aPuritanism.  aReformation.  aReligion and scienc.  aReligion and science.  aToleration.1 aIngram, Robert G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2018 eBook-Packagez978311128277040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152612695540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526126955423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526126955/original  a978-3-11-128277-0  Manchester University Press 2018 eBook-Packageb2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles